\begin_layout Title
Case Study: Maternal Labor Supply and Child Academic Outcomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This case study focuses on how a single mother, Lisa, allocates her time
 between work, child care, and leisure.
 The objective is to understand how different welfare reform policies might
 affect both Lisa's labor supply and her child's academic outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Scenario
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Meet Lisa, a single mother in her early 30s, who is contemplating how to
 allocate her time between work, child care, and leisure as she navigates
 various welfare reform policies.
 The time frame of the decision is one week (168 hours).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Setting Up the Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Given:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 = Consumption goods.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 = Leisure time measured in hours.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 = Time spent on maternal care measured in hours.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 = Time spent on work measured in hours.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 = Total available time in a week, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $m+l+L=T$
\end_inset

 (typically 
\begin_inset Formula $T=168$
\end_inset

 hours).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 = Price of consumption goods, assumed constant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 = Wage rate per hour.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 = Welfare benefits (converted to weekly income).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 = Academic outcome of the child, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=bm$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Utility Function:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lisa's utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $U(c,L,\theta)$
\end_inset

 captures her preferences for consumption, leisure, and her child's academic
 outcomes.
 The utility function is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(c,L,\theta)=c^{a}+L^{a}+\theta^{a}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq1$
\end_inset

, is a preference parameter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Budget Constraint:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before Reform: Lisa consumes 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 at prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, given labor income 
\begin_inset Formula $W\times l$
\end_inset

 before reform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After Reform: Lisa consumes 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 at prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, given labor income 
\begin_inset Formula $W\times l+B$
\end_inset

 after reform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Time Constraint:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before and After Reform:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m+l+L=T
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

