\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Optimal Welfare Reform: 
\series default
Assume the policy-maker aims to optimize their own utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 that reflects a weighted sum of the log of household income (through labor)
 and the log of the academic outcomes of children.
 For simplicity set 
\begin_inset Formula $w=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1/2,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $b=1/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T=168$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formally, this can be represented as: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z(B)=(l^{*2}(B))^{\delta}(\theta^{*2}(B))^{(1-\delta)}
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is a weight parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $(0\leq\delta\leq1)$
\end_inset

 that captures the policy-maker's preference between the two objectives.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $l^{*2}(B)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{*}(B)$
\end_inset

