\begin_layout Standard
How should the policy-maker optimally choose 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 to maximize 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

? Provide the mathematical formulation and solve it.
 Hint: This is equivalent to maximizing a univariate concave function without
 constraints that you learned in Calculus.
 Notice in this case there is no constraints (we are assuming away government
 financing here).
 Optimize for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

, explain the value, and obtain the optimal transfer under this parameter
 (it should be a positive quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $B>0$
\end_inset

), explain the economical logic on this result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Answer:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Replacing all the parameters we obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
l^{*2}(B)=\frac{2(168+B)}{5}-B
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\theta^{*2}(B)=\frac{168+B}{10}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then we obtain for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
